12 PART IV. FINANCIAL RELIEF MEASURES
13
14 MIDLIFE HEALTHCARE INDIVIDUAL TAX CREDIT AND BUSINESS TAX CREDIT
15 SECTION 4.1.(a) Article 4 of Chapter 105 of the General Statutes is amended by
16 adding two new sections to read:
17 "§ 105-153.12. Midlife healthcare individual tax credit.
18 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
19 (1) FDA. – The United States Food and Drug Administration.
20 (2) Expenses for midlife healthcare. – Expenses for any of the following:
21 a. Menopause-related treatments, including hormone therapy,
22 prescription medications, and medically recommended non-hormonal
23 alternatives.
24 b. Preventative health screenings, including mammograms, cervical
25 cancer screenings, osteoporosis screenings, and cardiovascular risk
26 assessments.
27 c. Chronic disease management, including treatment of diabetes,
28 hypertension, cholesterol issues, and other midlife-onset chronic
29 conditions.
30 d. Mental health services, including therapy or counseling related to
31 midlife hormonal changes, menopause-induced anxiety, and
32 depression.
33 e. Telehealth visits conducted for a treatment, screening, or service under
34 sub-subdivisions a. through d. of this subdivision.
35 (3) Expenses for menopause treatment. – Expenses for any FDA-approved
36 therapy, medication, or intervention prescribed by a licensed physician for
37 managing menopause symptoms, including the following:
38 a. Hormone replacement therapy.
39 b. Non-hormonal prescription treatments.
40 c. Prescription vaginal estrogen treatments.
41 (4) Expenses for prescription medications. – Expenses for FDA-approved
42 prescription medications that directly address midlife health concerns,
43 including osteoporosis, cardiovascular health, menopause, and diabetes.
44 (5) Out-of-pocket expenses. – The total of the following expenses that are not
45 reimbursed by health insurance:
46 a. Expenses for midlife healthcare.
47 b. Expenses for menopause treatment.
48 c. Expenses for prescription medications.
49 (b) Credit. – A taxpayer who has out-of-pocket expenses is allowed a credit against the
50 tax imposed by this Part equal to a percentage of the taxpayer's out-of-pocket expenses listed in
DRS45209-MGxfa-73A Page 3

